@5100 = ~You shouldn’t be wandering here at night. What do you want?~
@5101 = ~I have this coin — a token, I guess? I was told to bring it to someone behind the Temple of Helm here in the Bridge District. I believe it's meant for you.~
@5102 = ~Never mind. Farewell.~
@5103 = ~The token... so you’re the one they spoke of. I wasn’t sure anyone would come.~
@5104 = ~What are you talking about?~
@5105 = ~Well, here I am. Now what?~
@5106 = ~I figured I’d try my luck for once.~
@5107 = ~Interesting.~
@5108 = ~So what happens now?~
@5109 = ~Not much of a talker, are you?~
@5110 = ~I can’t tell you that. We only pass the message along. That’s all any of us ever do.~
@5111 = ~And what message is that?~
@5112 = ~Go to the Temple District — behind the Temple of Lathander, after nightfall. They’ll be waiting.~
@5113 = ~Who will be waiting there?~
@5114 = ~Waiting for what?~
@5115 = ~The one you asked to help you get what you wanted.~
@5116 = ~I never said what I wanted.~
@5117 = ~What was it I wanted again?~
@5118 = ~For you, I suppose. Or for what you wanted.~
@5119 = ~Only you can know that.~
@5120 = ~And what if I’ve forgotten it?~
@5121 = ~Maybe you’ll find out there. My part in this is done. Farewell.~
@5122 = ~Then keep moving. Night’s not safe for those without purpose.~
@5123 = ~You came. I wasn’t sure you’d find the place.~
@5124 = ~I was told to meet someone here — behind Lathander’s temple. I still don’t know what this token is supposed to mean.~
@5125 = ~I think I’ve made a mistake. Farewell.~
@5126 = ~You’re not the first to say that. It’s not for us to know — we only send you on.~
@5127 = ~Then where am I supposed to go next?~
@5128 = ~I’m being sent on again?~
@5129 = ~Go to the Government District. At the Temple of Waukeen, after nightfall. The one you’re seeking will be waiting there.~
@5130 = ~And what am I supposed to get there?~
@5131 = ~Good. It’s about time I got a reward for all this running around.~
@5132 = ~Whatever it is you’ve been looking for.~
@5133 = ~Couldn’t you give me the slightest hint what that was supposed to be again?~
@5134 = ~It seems no one actually wants to tell me what’s going on.~
@5135 = ~Go to the Government District, then — before the dawn finds you.~
@5136 = ~Then go. The night here doesn’t tolerate strays.~
@5137 = ~Well now... I didn’t expect anyone to actually show up with that thing.~
@5138 = ~This token’s taken me across half the city. I was told to meet someone here, at the Temple of Waukeen.~
@5139 = ~Forget it. I’ve had enough of this chase.~
@5140 = ~Then you’ve come further than most. Most turn back before they reach the gold gates.~
@5141 = ~And what am I supposed to find here?~
@5142 = ~Gold is a fine word. Perhaps you’ve got some for me?~
@5143 = ~Everyone wants to find something. Profit, answers, absolution... doesn’t matter which.~
@5144 = ~So what now?~
@5145 = ~I’m not that picky.~
@5146 = ~Now you keep going. The last of us meets behind the Temple of Ilmater — down in the Slums, after nightfall. He’ll know what to do with you.~
@5147 = ~And what will he tell me?~
@5148 = ~The last of you? Now that gives me hope.~
@5149 = ~How should I know? I’ve no idea what you asked him for.~
@5150 = ~You don’t sound convinced.~
@5151 = ~Neither do I.~
@5152 = ~I just mind the message — and I’ve delivered it. Go on, before someone sees you here.~
@5153 = ~Suit yourself. There’s always someone else chasing promises.~
@5154 = ~You’ve come a long way to stand in a place most people avoid.~
@5155 = ~I was told to meet someone behind Ilmater’s temple. I suppose that’s you.~
@5156 = ~I must have taken a wrong turn. Farewell.~
@5157 = ~Yes, I’ve been waiting for you. They said you’d bring the token, though no one could tell me why.~
@5158 = ~Everyone keeps saying I’ll get what I wanted. So — what is it I’m supposed to find here?~
@5159 = ~So why don’t you just say it — what is there for me to gain here?~
@5160 = ~I’ve come too far for more riddles — tell me what I GET.~
@5161 = ~In your letter, you asked me to lift your geas. Have you forgotten already?~
@5162 = ~Ah... right. That. Of course.~
@5163 = ~A geas? What geas?~
@5164 = ~I sense no geas upon you. You are not the one who wrote to me for aid.~
@5165 = ~Honestly, I found your letter on a corpse somewhere out in the wilderness.~
@5166 = ~Oh, never mind. Just cast some other useful spell on me, then.~
@5167 = ~If not a geas, I’d gladly settle for some gold instead.~
@5168 = ~Hold on — I’ll see if any of my party members might need your help.~
@5169 = ~Then the matter that burdened that man has already resolved itself — one way or another.~
@5170 = ~I’m sorry — that is beyond me.~
@5171 = ~I have nothing further to give you — nothing save what you already carry with you.~
@5172 = ~That was a damned useless quest.~
@5173 = ~So all of this was for nothing?~
@5174 = ~Perhaps. But take one good lesson with you: Not all journeys end with treasure — some end when we stop searching.~
@5175 = ~My work here is done. Farewell.~
@5176 = ~Then go. Some burdens are better left untouched.~
@5177 = ~The coin is yours once more. Its purpose has faded with the passing centuries, yet a trace of the old magic remains. Perhaps fate will grant you cause to use it. Farewell.~